    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1963-08-31T09:15:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1963-08-31T09:15:00-05:00" n="36"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d36">
                <head>36. Memorandum of Telephone Conversation Between the Secretary of State and
                    the Assistant Secretary of State for Far Eastern Affairs (<persName
                        corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName>)<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d36fn1">Source: Department of State, <persName corresp="#p_RD1"
                            >Rusk</persName> Files: Lot 72 D 192, Telephone Conversations.
                        Transcribed by Mildred Asbjornson.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" type="conversation-or-meeting-date"
                            when="1963-08-31T10:15:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 31, 1963—10:15 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">TELEPHONE CALL FROM <gloss target="#t_AMB1">AMB</gloss>. <persName
                        corresp="#p_HWA1">HARRIMAN</persName>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_AMB1">Amb</gloss>. <persName corresp="#p_HWA1"
                        >Harriman</persName> said he would come back to Washington if need be. He
                    did not think events entirely surprising (Vietnam). He thought we should go back
                    to the program we recommended a week ago,<note n="2" xml:id="d36fn2">Apparent
                        reference to telegram 243 to Saigon, <ref target="frus1961-63v03#pg_628"
                            >vol. III, p. 628</ref>.</note> and have it out. He thought we should
                    tell <persName corresp="#p_DIEM1">Diem</persName> what we were going to do and
                    stick to it. We had gone through the same thing with Phoumi.<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d36fn3">Reference is to <persName corresp="#p_HWA1"
                            >Harriman</persName>’s efforts to convince Phoumi Nosovan to cooperate
                        with U.S. support of a neutralized Laos.</note>
                    <persName corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName> asked if the Sec had seen
                        <persName corresp="#p_KPM1">Kattenburg</persName>. The Sec said he had but
                    that Kattenburg’s report<note n="4" xml:id="d36fn4">
                        <persName corresp="#p_RD1">Rusk</persName> apparently is referring to
                        Kattenburg’s point of view, set forth in the memorandum of conversation <ref
                            target="#d37">
                            <hi rend="italic">infra</hi>
                        </ref>.</note> was already out of date in some important respects.</p>
                <p>The Sec. said either he or Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HRJ1">Hilsman</persName>
                    would be in touch with <gloss target="#t_AMB1">Amb</gloss>. <persName
                        corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName> later in the day.</p>
            </div>
